word_summaries_chapter_99:
  99:1:1:"The first word of verse (99:1) is a time adverb."
  99:1:2:"The second word of verse (99:1) is a passive perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person feminine singular. The verb's quadriliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">zāy lām zāy lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ز ل ز ل</span>)."
  99:1:3:"The third word of verse (99:1) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza rā ḍād</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ر ض</span>)."
  99:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's quadriliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">zāy lām zāy lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ز ل ز ل</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person feminine singular."
  99:2:1:"The first word of verse (99:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and verb. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person feminine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā rā jīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ر ج</span>)."
  99:2:2:"The second word of verse (99:2) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza rā ḍād</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ر ض</span>)."
  99:2:3:"The third word of verse (99:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine plural and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">thā qāf lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ث ق ل</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person feminine singular."
  99:3:1:"The first word of verse (99:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and verb. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf wāw lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق و ل</span>)."
  99:3:2:"The second word of verse (99:3) is a masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza nūn sīn</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ن س</span>)."
  99:3:3:"The third word of verse (99:3) is an interrogative noun."
  99:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The personal pronoun is third person feminine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  99:4:1:"The first word of verse (99:4) is a time adverb."
  99:4:2:"The second word of verse (99:4) is a form II imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person feminine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā dāl thā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح د ث</span>)."
  99:4:3:"The third word of verse (99:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine plural and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā bā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ب ر</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person feminine singular."
  99:5:1:"The first word of verse (99:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and accusative particle. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The accusative particle belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>)."
  99:5:2:"The second word of verse (99:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  99:5:3:"The third word of verse (99:5) is a form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw ḥā yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ح ي</span>)."
  99:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and personal pronoun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The personal pronoun is third person feminine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  99:6:1:"The first word of verse (99:6) is a time adverb."
  99:6:2:"The second word of verse (99:6) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād dāl rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص د ر</span>)."
  99:6:3:"The third word of verse (99:6) is a masculine plural noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn wāw sīn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن و س</span>)."
  99:6:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:6) is an indefinite masculine plural noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn tā tā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ت ت</span>)."
  99:6:5:"The fifth word of verse (99:6) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A particle of purpose, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is used to indicate the purpose of an action and makes the following verb subjunctive. The passive form IV imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine plural and is in the subjunctive mood (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  99:6:6:"The sixth word of verse (99:6) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine plural and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn mīm lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع م ل</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  99:7:1:"The first word of verse (99:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A resumption particle and conditional noun. The connective particle <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"then\" or \"so\" and is used to indicate a sequence of events."
  99:7:2:"The second word of verse (99:7) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn mīm lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع م ل</span>)."
  99:7:3:"The third word of verse (99:7) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">thā qāf lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ث ق ل</span>)."
  99:7:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:7) is an indefinite feminine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dhāl rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ذ ر ر</span>)."
  99:7:5:"The fifth word of verse (99:7) is an indefinite masculine singular noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā yā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ي ر</span>)."
  99:7:6:"The sixth word of verse (99:7) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine singular."
  99:8:1:"The first word of verse (99:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and conditional noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  99:8:2:"The second word of verse (99:8) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn mīm lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع م ل</span>)."
  99:8:3:"The third word of verse (99:8) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">thā qāf lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ث ق ل</span>)."
  99:8:4:"The fourth word of verse (99:8) is an indefinite feminine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dhāl rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ذ ر ر</span>)."
  99:8:5:"The fifth word of verse (99:8) is an indefinite masculine singular noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ر ر</span>)."
  99:8:6:"The sixth word of verse (99:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine singular."